  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improving the quality of primary education (10-15ys) across the Western Balkans through  critical thinking, problem solving and coding skills for students</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">21st Century Schools programme is supporting around 1 million 10-15-year-old students across all public primary schools in the Western Balkans to build their capacities in coding, critical thinking and problem-solving skills.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Additionally, the programme works with national policy-makers across the Western Balkans region, to ensure they encourage schools to take up the training and, where needed, support the introduction of critical thinking, problem solving and coding skills in schools with relevant policy changes (curriculum reform, teacher continuous professional development policy, etc.).</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To accomplish its objectives, the programme will:

a.	Expose around 18,000 teachers to a training programme and enable them to effectively teach critical thinking, problem solving and coding skills in the classroom with the use of micro:bit, pocket programmable computer. 
b.	Target school leaders to enhance their capacities to lead, promote and implement critical thinking, problem solving and coding skills across curriculum in their schools. 
c.	Provide schools with resources to effectively teach coding skills to students. This includes supplying schools with micro:bit devices, small computational devices which offer a physical dimension to the experience of learning how to compute. Each of 4000 schools across the Western Balkans will receive between 10 and 60 micro:bit devices through the programme, depending on the number of pupils in the school.</narrative>
  </description>
